Hi Company_E—thanks again. As requested, here’s a 1-page (bulleted) first-30-days plan for an execution-focused Program/Ops lane, plus constraints.

First 30 days plan (how I’d run it)
Days 1–5: Align + map the work
- Confirm the single most urgent outcomes for the seat (top 3 priorities, success metrics, and what “done” means).
- Stakeholder map + 1:1s with key partners (Ops/Product/Eng/Support/etc.) to capture pain points and dependencies.
- Inventory current initiatives, timelines, owners, and risks; identify any “at-risk” deliverables.
- Establish operating cadence: weekly exec summary, project tracker, risk/decision log, and a clear escalation path.

Days 6–15: Stabilize execution + remove bottlenecks
- Stand up/refresh RACI and SLAs for the critical workflow(s); ensure ownership is unambiguous.
- Create a single source of truth (lightweight dashboard + tracker) and automate the most manual status collection where possible.
- Run the first 1–2 cycles of the cadence (weekly review, action items, follow-ups) and close obvious gaps.
- Surface top risks early with options/asks (tradeoffs, resourcing, sequencing).

Days 16–30: Deliver measurable wins + scale the system
- Drive at least one end-to-end deliverable to completion (or a clear milestone) with measurable impact (cycle time, on-time rate, fewer escalations, etc.).
- Tighten cross-functional handoffs (templates, checklists, comms plan, cutover/runbook if relevant).
